<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=289901">Furye Gnofear - SoulBonded</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nalarine>Nalarine</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/24/03 4:49 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Smoking!!!!</span><hr size=1> Dizzera and Maurley, you are on the right track - that's exactly how I quit.  A few years ago I managed to quit for three months, but my boyfriend refused to quit (or even be supportive) so I ended up starting again.  But I didn't go back to smoking while at work.  Then I got a new car and was determined not to smoke in it.  Then I moved into a house with some friends who didn't smoke inside.  By eliminating it a little at a time (but over the course of about a year), I realized I was down to less than a pack a week.  So as a New Year's resolution I gave it up for good.  I have had some moments of weakness at the bars (probably smoked about a dozen cigarettes this year) but the important thing the next day is to just let it go and continue to be a non-smoker.<br>
<br>
It really helps to have supportive friends.  Tell everyone you're trying to cut back or quit.  My mom actually offered me a &quot;prize&quot; if I could go six months without smoking - even though I've fallen off the wagon, that's definitely an incentive to keep trying.  If you don't have a friend or family member to offer you some kind of reward, maybe you can plan to treat yourself to something once you reach a short-term goal.<br>
<br>
You can do it - good luck!!! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=magno1>Magno1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/27/03 7:57 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Smoking!!!!</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>glad you quit, honestly....most non-smokers cant stand to be around smokers no matter what they say smokers stink, literally<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Tomb Based on that statement I am assuming you have never smoked.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>If</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that is the case the maybe you should not make any comments on how, when, or why someone didn’t succeed in quitting.  It is honestly the hardest thing a smoker will ever do.<br>
<br>
Dizzera I am pulling for ya.  I did manage to quit for six months about 5 years ago.  I have managed to get my smoking down to about a pack every three days.  The biggest thing in quitting is that you need to really want to quit.  Let me rephrase that, quitting because someone wants you to or because you can’t smoke some places isn’t going to work.  You have to want to quit.  I guess that is why I have not quit totally.  I don’t want to.  I am sure when I want to do it I will give it another go but I know how hard it was the first time around and really don’t feel like going through it just now.<br>
<br>
As far as the quit drinking thing, it is by far easier to quit drinking than it is to quit smoking.  I go on the wagon every lent and I do it without any problems.  I don’t have the burning urge to drink a beer after I eat dinner, after laying the pipe to the ole lady or when I am stressed out like I do with cigarettes.<br>
<br>
I’m sure you will get there.  Just incase good luck………<br>
